  "prompt": "How are bra sizes measured?",
  "response": "Bra sizes are typically measured using two components:\n\n1. Band size (chest measurement):\n- Measure around the ribcage, directly under the breasts\n- Round to the nearest whole number\n- Add 4-5 inches if the measurement is even, or 5-6 if odd\n- This becomes the band size (e.g., 32, 34, 36)\n\n2. Cup size (breast volume):\n- Measure around the fullest part of the bust\n- Subtract the band size from this measurement\n- The difference determines the cup size:\n0\" = AA\n1\" = A\n2\" = B\n3\" = C\n4\" = D\n5\" = DD/E\n6\" = DDD/F\nAnd so on...\n\nExample: If your ribcage measures 30\" and bust measures 36\", your size would be 34C.\n\nProfessional fittings are recommended for the most accurate sizing, as measuring can be complex and brands may vary slightly.",
